#   Keeper: the local git object store

Keeper is the object-store dog: its purview is git object storage, and it owns those objects ‚Äî append-only `NNNNN.keeper` pack logs, their `NNNNN.keeper.idx` kv64 indexes, and a project `refs` reflog, one flat shard per project. The goal is a store trivially git-exchangeable yet never rewriting packs, so packs copy verbatim and a dropped branch costs only a `refs` tombstone. The method: address by 60-bit hashlets, append to pack logs, index as sorted kv64 runs, resolve deltas within the single project pool.

 -  Pack logs are append-only, git-encoded but not valid packfiles (no trailing checksum); offsets stay stable, never moved.
 -  OFS_DELTA bases are pack-local (a stable earlier offset); REF_DELTA bases resolve by hashlet within the one project pool.
 -  The kv64 index sorts `hashlet60|type4` keys, so a hash-prefix lookup is one range query spanning all object types.
 -  Dropping a branch is a `refs` tombstone, not a dir delete: objects linger in the shard until an epoch recompaction.
 -  Refs and host aliases live in the project `refs` reflog; a branch's refs is authoritative ‚Äî resolution does not walk up.

##  API

Keeper follows the [Dog] three-call contract plus an incremental pack writer; objects are read by hashlet or URI and written through the pack API.

 -  `KEEPOpen` / `KEEPOpenBranch` / `KEEPClose` ‚Äî open the store, select a branch's tips within the one shard, then close it.
 -  `KEEPExec(state, cli)` ‚Äî run a parsed verb plus URIs against the open store.
 -  `KEEPGet` / `KEEPGetByURI` ‚Äî read an object by hashlet or by a full URI into a buffer.
 -  `KEEPLookup` ‚Äî range-query the kv64 index across the project pool, returning `(file_id, offset)` for the first hit.
 -  `KEEPHas` / `KEEPGetSize` ‚Äî existence and size probes by hashlet.
 -  `KEEPPackOpen` / `KEEPPackFeed` / `KEEPPackClose` ‚Äî incremental pack writer; `Feed` appends one object and returns its sha.
 -  `KEEPResolveRef` / `KEEPResolveHex` ‚Äî resolve a `?ref` or a hex prefix to a full sha.
 -  `KEEPIsAncestor` ‚Äî ancestry test backing the ff-only push and advance checks.

##  CLI

The `keeper` CLI clones, fetches, resolves, and cats by URI, plus a few maintenance verbs; `be` normally drives it rather than the user.

 -  `keeper get //host/path` clones, `//host?tags/v6.0` fetches a ref, `.?heads/master` resolves, `.#abc1234` cats an object.
 -  `keeper refs` lists refs, `keeper import pack` ingests a git packfile, `keeper status` shows store stats.
 -  `keeper verify .#sha` checks a commit and all reachable objects; `keeper alias //name url` records a host alias.

##  Pack logs

Pack logs are append-only, git-encoded object files ‚Äî close to git's packfile format but not valid git packfiles, with no trailing checksum; see [PackLog] for the full format.

 -  The first batch keeps a standard PACK header from `git-upload-pack`; later fetches and `KEEPPackFeed` append objects.
 -  OFS_DELTA references are pack-local ‚Äî the base sits earlier in the same pack at a stable offset, so packs copy verbatim.
 -  Objects are never moved or rewritten; offsets stay stable. Logs use mmap'd growable `FILEBook`, read via `FILEMapRO`.

##  Index (kv64)

Each index entry is 16 bytes ‚Äî a u64 key and u64 val ‚Äî sorted by hashlet then type, so a hash-prefix lookup is one range query over all types; see [Indices] for the shared sorted-run format.

 -  `key = hashlet60 | obj_type4` (commit/tree/blob/tag in the low 4 bits); `val = offset40 | file_id20 | flags4`, wh64 layout.
 -  `file_id` is the store-wide `NNNNN` of the pack log; it resolves to a file in the single project shard, no per-dir search.
 -  Index runs are per-project sorted kv64 files: write sorts and flushes, read binary-searches, compact merges on breach.

##  Delta dependencies and branch drop

All of a project's objects share one flat pool; a REF_DELTA may delta against any earlier object in that pool, with no cross-project base, which keeps each shard self-contained.

 -  REF_DELTA resolves by hashlet lookup in the single project pool; never delta against another project's object ‚Äî forbidden.
 -  Dropping a branch is a `refs` tombstone: objects linger in the shard; GC is an out-of-band epoch recompaction, not a delete.
 -  Resolution: range-query the project index, read at `(file_id, offset)`, chase the delta chain bottom-up ‚Äî no walk-up.

##  Refs and aliases

The project `<project>/refs` is an append-only reflog (a `dog/ULOG`) holding every branch, tag, and host alias as rows; the verb is always `set` and the key/val pair is packed into one URI.

 -  A row is `<ron60-ms>\tset\t<from-uri>#?<40-hex-sha>`; `REFSLoad` splits on `#` to return `{key,val}`, ts monotonic.
 -  A local tip uses a query-only key (`?heads/main#?<sha>`); remote-tracking a full origin (`//origin/path?heads/feat#?<sha>`).
 -  Host aliases ride the same file with a URL fragment (`//github#?https://‚Ä¶`); a branch's refs is authoritative, no walk-up.

